Switch to using HTTPS

The game itself now uses HTTPS by default, so lets do that ourselves.

Have Thunk::process return a mutable reference

Otherwise, it would not be possible to get a mutable reference to a
thunk's processed data without explicitly pattern matching.

Add Thunk::as_processed

Prior to this, there was no non-mutating function implemented on `Thunk`
that allowed to retrieve a processed value (`process` modified the thunk
in-place, and `into_processed` consumed the thunk). The cost of this
ability is the requirement for `ThunkProcessor::Output`'s lifetime to
become covariant (as otherwise, the lifetimes of the Thunk::Processed
and Thunk::Unprocessed branches would be unreconcilable, with the former
being tied to &self, and the latter being 'a). This should not be a big
limitation in praxis though.

Change CI autoformat to use stable toolchain

It used to use the nightly toolchain because back when I started working
on dash-rs, I was using a nightly toolchain (mainly because pointercrate
required unstable features). Nowadays, I only have a stable
toolchain, and that means my IDE is formatting differently than the CI.
I dont particularly care _how_ stuff is formatted, only that it is
formatted consistently, so remove all nightly-only options from
rustfmt.toml and have the CI also use a stable toolchain.

Add feature flag to statically disable logging in serde module

Turns out that since this is a hot path, even with the log level set to
warn (e.g. no logs actually being emitted), this had a ~10% performance
impact.

Also get rid of the `last_token` field, I forgot that for non-hot-paths
(such as error reporting and logging), we already have the `nth_last`
function.
Add deserialization test for "input ends with delimiter"

Remove helper.rs

All tests have been updated to the new test framework

Remove usage of helper.rs from tests/misc.rs

The only usage was a call to .load(), which itself just called
from_gj_str, so inline it.

Switch tests/comment.rs to new test framework

For now, I can't really think of a good way to add a refresh
functionality for these, so I manually converted the artifacts (they
were targetting specific comments left by specific people with specific
permissions).
Use new test framework for SearchedUser model tests

Add new 2.2 index to SearchUser

This being the "moon count" is a best-guess, as index 52 is the moon
count in the `Profile` structure. It is always zero (e.g. both diamonds
and moons are bugged in-game and always show as "0" when searching for
users).
Use new test framework for NewgroundsSong model tests

Use new test framework for creator tests

Also derive `VariantPartialEq` for `Creator` (as its a requirement of
the generic bounds in the new framework), and teach the framework how to
deal with non-map-like responses.

Use new test framework for listed levels

The new example code also creates artifacts for creator and newgrounds
song model tests. These will be added in the next commits.

Rename Profile::index_53 to jetpack_index

Someone who actually played the net platformer levels informed me that
this is what it's called. Also correctly type this and sing_index as u8
instead of string.

Add new 2.2 song to MAIN_SONGS array

Is it really called "Geometry Dash"? Sounds like the guy in the song
says "Triometry Dash", and the associated level is called "Dash"... Oh
well.

Use new test framework for Level<'a, LevelData<'a>, _, _> tests

This has the advantage to also run through `Objects`'s deserialization
routine, without having to hardcode its output in the test file (it is
part of the new artifacts).

fix `MainSong` deserialization

Since the artist and song_name fields were marked as `#[serde(skip)]`,
they were always set to the empty string after deserializing. Fix this
by actually serializing to u8 as the comment specifies, upon which the
lookup map is used to determine artist and song_name.

derive VariantPartialEq for LevelData

This is needed for full levels to work with the generic testing
framework

Add `Testable::canonicalize`

This plays the same role as `ThunkProcessor::process_all_thunks`, with
slightly more general semantics. If we do a save->load roundtrip, all
thunks needs to be evaluated at the end, as the "processed" artifacts
have all their thunks evaluated. If we do a load->save roundtrip, we
want to evaluate all thunks in the middle to ensure that evaluating
thunks does not break serializability.
Use new test framework for Profile tests

Framework for discovering and testing artifacts

Implements a generic discovery mechanism for all artifacts of a given
type, and methods to do the consistency test and roundtrip tests. This
will lead to "frankentests", as a single test will now do tests across a
multitude of artifacts, but c'est la vie.

Have test artifacts be generated by an "example"

Each artifact consists of two files, both generated at the same time: A
raw response from the Geometry Dash servers, and a serde_json dump of
the processed version of that response (as dash-rs would interpret it at
the time of creating the artifacts). Each test should then dynamically
disocver all artifacts of a given type, assert their consistency (e.g.
processing the response still gives the same dash-rs structure), and can
then do round trip testing using these artifacts.

Have Profile derive VariantPartialEq

This will be needed for generic test code

Update Profile struct with 2.2 indices

Two new games modes, one new collectible, and one mystery index.

fix: add missing .php extension to user requests

Apparently no one ever tried to use these in the last 5 years, lol.

Update tests to work with new Level indices

Also regenerate the misc.rs artifacts by redownloading the repsective
levels.

Add "example" that regenerates the test artifacts

For now it only regenerates the artifacts used for the tests in misc.rs.
Pending some refractoring of our integration testing, it should be able
to download all objects that are used in our integration tests.
Add support for new 2.2 indices to downloadGJLevel22.php

Add support for platform levels

A level's Platformer-ness is encoded by a special variant in the
LevelLength enumeration.

Improve logging on ignored tokens

The Deserializer now also logs the previous token, to more easily
identify which indices are unmapped. The message is not also logged at
debug! level instead of trace! level, so that they are easier to filter
out from the noise of trace-level logs.

Upgrade default BaseRequest data to GD 2.2

Geometry Dash 2.2 adds no additional BaseRequest fields, but updates
game_version and binary_version. Some endpoints now reject requests made
by a 2.1 client (for example downloadGJLevel)

Do not assert on Result::is_ok

Instead just call .unwrap(), which has the same effect in a test, and
also gives better error messages.

Remove now-unneeded HasRobtopFormat trait

This trait is the predecessor to `Dash`. Also remove the build.rs-based
infrastructure for generating the internal (de)serialization structures,
and mapping from indices to API fields.

Use Dash-based API for Level structs

We cannot use #[derive(Dash)] here, because the derive macro does not
support the `LevelData` field. This is because we have two responses
(getGJLevel and downloadGJLevel) that map into the same struct, with the
former being a subset of the latter's indices. Supporting this would be
difficult, so for now just use a manual implementation of Dash here.

Allow zero lifetimes on #[derive(Dash)] input

Not having any lifetime means that the structure does not borrow
anything from the input during deserialization. In this case, all
InternalProxy implementations for fields on the input struct need to
return something with 'static, while the Dash trait itself is still
implemented for all possible input lifetimes.

Add support for non-numeric indices

Level metadata and plist formats use non-numeric indices, so support
these in the derive macro.

User Dash trait instead of HasRobtopFormat for LevelObject

While the ability to _derive_ Dash here is a far out dream, we can at
least switch the manual conversion implementation to the new Dash API

Allow Dash-derived structs to have unmapped fields

These fields do not correspond to internal indices in any way, and are
initialized to Default::default() during deserialization.

dash-rs-derive: Pass unrecognized attributes to serde

Whwnever a `dash` attribute is unrecognized by dash-rs-derive, assume
its contents are meant as a `#[serde(...)]` annotation for the internal
structure.

Use #[derive(Dash)] for ProfileComment

This one is also a direct 1:1 mapping to indexed data

Use #[derive(Dash)] for NewgroundsSong

The NewgroundsSong struct is the easiest to apply it to, as it is a
1:1 mapping to the indexed representation.

Duplicates parts of the test code to be able to deal with both the old
`HasRobtopFormat` API, and the new `Dash`/`GJFormat` APIs. This will
deduplicate again once all models are converted.

Add #[derive(Dash)] proc-macro

Adds a minimal version of a derive macro that can generate dash-rs'
"internal" representations of GD structs. For now, it only works for
structs where every field in the public API is a 1:1 mapping of some
index in the Geometry Dash format.

The proc-macro implements the `Dash` trait, which will replace the
`HasRobtopFormat` trait. This trait allows (de)serialization based on
an indexed data format using a generic (de)serializer. This decouples
the derive from the string-based format used in GD's HTTP responses,
meaning the Dash macro can also be used for types that describe indexed
objects from, say, the plist save files. The old string-based API moved
into a new subtrait `GJFormat`, which can be implemented for types
implementing `Dash`, and which provides the old APIs from
`HasRobtopFormat`.

Add dash-rs-derive crate

This crate will contain a derive proc-macro for generating the
"internal" presentations of Geometry Dash data structures (which is
currently done via yaml descriptions + build script).

Use thiserror

Allows us to have less boilerplate impl Display/From for [...]Error code
Add examples and tests to "check" GitHub action
test: Add unittest for indexed deserializer

Add examples directory to show off dash-rs usage

The example is a short script that start downloading (and locally
storing) featured level if they are in-game copyable.
Make it possible for Thunks to own unprocessed data

Remove now-unneeded new-type wrappers

We previously needed the Base64Decoded and PercentDecoded newtype
wrappers to be able to implement ThunkContent on them. Since now the
type of a processed Thunk variant is described via an associated type,
this is no longer necessary.

This also reduces the nesting of types inside thunks.

Have Thunk leverage generic associated types

To be able to have a Thunk own unprocessed data, we need to be able to
have the ThunkContent::from_unprocessed (now
ThunkProcessor::from_unprocessed) be able to process arbitrarily
borrowed input. This means that the signature of the funciton has to be
fn<'a>(&'a str) -> Output<'a>, where Output<'a> is a GAT.

There are some troubles with GATs causing lifetimes to be invariant,
which is why we now pull in VariantPartialEq as a drop-in replacement
for PartialEq derives.

Put passwords into a Thunk

This removes the need for Internal<T>, as well as prevents
robtop-deserialization from failing on malformed passwords.

Remove RefThunk

The complexity of this was not needed, as the "internal" version of each
struct does not accidentally need the ability to hold a borrowed
"Thunk::Processed" variant. It only needs to hold the unprocessed
string.

This commit changes the generated boilerplate code to do
"as_unprocessed" calls to convert Thunks into &str (previously, this
only happened in the Serialize implementation of RefThunk).

Pass --keep-only src/* to grcov

This ensures that the coverage reports only contains files inside the
project. Without this, it will also contain coverage information for
dependencies and other things in the GitHub Runner file system, which
was confusing codecov.io.

Prior to this, there was no non-mutating function implemented on `Thunk`
that allowed to retrieve a processed value (`process` modified the thunk
in-place, and `into_processed` consumed the thunk). The cost of this
ability is the requirement for `ThunkProcessor::Output`'s lifetime to
become covariant (as otherwise, the lifetimes of the Thunk::Processed
and Thunk::Unprocessed branches would be unreconcilable, with the former
being tied to &self, and the latter being 'a). This should not be a big
limitation in praxis though.

Add #[derive(Dash)] proc-macro

Adds a minimal version of a derive macro that can generate dash-rs'
"internal" representations of GD structs. For now, it only works for
structs where every field in the public API is a 1:1 mapping of some
index in the Geometry Dash format.

The proc-macro implements the `Dash` trait, which will replace the
`HasRobtopFormat` trait. This trait allows (de)serialization based on
an indexed data format using a generic (de)serializer. This decouples
the derive from the string-based format used in GD's HTTP responses,
meaning the Dash macro can also be used for types that describe indexed
objects from, say, the plist save files. The old string-based API moved
into a new subtrait `GJFormat`, which can be implemented for types
implementing `Dash`, and which provides the old APIs from
`HasRobtopFormat`.

currently done via yaml descriptions + build script).

Remove now-unneeded new-type wrappers

We previously needed the Base64Decoded and PercentDecoded newtype
wrappers to be able to implement ThunkContent on them. Since now the
type of a processed Thunk variant is described via an associated type,
this is no longer necessary.

This also reduces the nesting of types inside thunks.
Have Thunk leverage generic associated types

To be able to have a Thunk own unprocessed data, we need to be able to
have the ThunkContent::from_unprocessed (now
ThunkProcessor::from_unprocessed) be able to process arbitrarily
borrowed input. This means that the signature of the funciton has to be
fn<'a>(&'a str) -> Output<'a>, where Output<'a> is a GAT.

There are some troubles with GATs causing lifetimes to be invariant,
which is why we now pull in VariantPartialEq as a drop-in replacement
for PartialEq derives.
Put passwords into a Thunk

This removes the need for Internal<T>, as well as prevents
robtop-deserialization from failing on malformed passwords.
Remove RefThunk

The complexity of this was not needed, as the "internal" version of each
struct does not accidentally need the ability to hold a borrowed
"Thunk::Processed" variant. It only needs to hold the unprocessed
string.

This commit changes the generated boilerplate code to do
"as_unprocessed" calls to convert Thunks into &str (previously, this
only happened in the Serialize implementation of RefThunk).
Pass --keep-only src/* to grcov

This ensures that the coverage reports only contains files inside the
project. Without this, it will also contain coverage information for
